entry.title: Project Report
entry.summary:
Twenty Years of Flight Delays in the United States¶

Jonathan Chen, Connie Fee, Steven Hu, Bob Shao
Department of Statistics
University of California, Berkeley

Team Members Responsible for this Notebook

  • Jonathan Chen: consolidating information, writeup
  • Steven Hu: consolidating information, writeup
  • Bob Shao: consolidating information, writeup

Objective

In this data analysis project, we investigated flights originating from the 20 busiest United States airports by passenger boarding. Our goal was to determine which of the airports was the "worst" in terms of flight delays. Passengers typically expect their flights to depart and arrive on-time, but time and time again flights are delayed or cancelled. In fact, in the time span between 1987 and 2008, 25 million flights, over 20%, were delayed by at least 15 minutes. That's a lot of frustrated flyers!

There are several different ways to quantify the word "worst." It's difficult to determine a singular metric for determining the "worst" airport, but the metrics we used include the following:

  • Average delay duration, all flights
  • Average delay duration, delayed flights only
  • Proportion of flights delayed, 1 minute or more
  • Proportion of flights delayed, over x minutes
  • Delays over time (1987-2008)

These metrics all are of interest to prospective travelers, but each individual traveler may find certain metrics more meaningful than others. For example, consider airport A that has 80% delayed flights, but an average delay of 5 minutes, versus airport B with 10% delayed flights, but an average delay of 50 minutes. Depending on personal preferences, it it difficult to evaluate and make general conclusions when comparing the two airports directly against each other.

For now, we will simply look at the numbers for each metric, but we will return to the question of evaluation later.

Data Gathering

We pulled flight data from 1987 to 2008 from http://stat-computing.org/dataexpo/2009/the-data.html.

The files contain data on all domestic US commercial flights from 1987 to 2008, representing 29 commercial airlines and 3376 airports. The data from all years combined consist of over 120 million rows and 29 columns. Each row represents a flight. The columns include (but are not limited to) the following information:

  • Year
  • Month
  • Day of Month
  • Day of Week
  • Scheduled Departure Time
  • Actual Departure Time
  • Scheduled Arrival Time
  • Actual Arrival Time
  • Scheduled Flight Time
  • Actual Flight Time
  • Departure Delay
  • Arrival Delay
  • Airport of Origin
  • Destination Airport
  • Flight Distance
  • Flight Number

The large size of the raw data made it impossible to work with directly in the iPython Notebook. To set the groundwork for the data analysis, we constructed an SQL database using SQLite.

Using the database, we were able to look up and pull the data we wanted as we needed it, instead of attempting to load the data into RAM (which would not have worked due to the sheer size). The gathering process is documented in more detail in NB1.

Narrowing the Scope

We first filtered the data and found the top 20 airports by number of originating flights. For our purposes, these would serve as the major airports we would investigate. The top 20 airports accounted for just over half of all flights between them.

Below is the list of the 20 busiest airports in the United States that we considered:

  • ORD - Chicago O'Hare International Airport
  • ATL - Hartsfield-Jackson Atlanta International Airport
  • DFW - Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport
  • LAX - Los Angeles International Airport
  • PHX - Phoenix Sky Harbor International Airport
  • DEN - Denver International Airport
  • DTW - Detroit Metropolitan Wayne County Airport
  • IAH - George Bush Intercontinental Airport
  • MSP - Minneapolis-SaintPaul International Airport Code
  • SFO - San Francisco International Airport
  • STL - Lambert-St. Louis International Airport
  • EWR - Newark Liberty International Airport
  • LAS - McCarran International Airport
  • CLT - Charlotte Douglas International Airport
  • LGA - LaGuardia Airport
  • BOS - Logan International Airport
  • PHL - Philadelphia International Airport
  • PIT - Pittsburgh International Airport
  • SLC - Salt Lake City International Airport
  • SEA - Seattle Tacoma International Airport

These airports are the focus of our analysis.

Data Cleaning

We pulled the relevant flights for each airport out of the database and saved them as CSV (with Python scripts). After filtering out unnecessary columns, we made additional modifications based on the delays.

Cancelled flights are removed, flights outside (-60, 500) for delay are removed to remove outliers (see NB2 for an in-depth discussion), and all negative delays (early flights) are set to 0. This is because in evaluating delayed flights, an early flight is essentially the same as an on-time flight. It doesn't make sense to say that an airport that has 3 flights, with delays -5, 0, and 5, has an average delay of 0 minutes.

Data Analysis

More discussion, and the code, can be found in NB3, here is a summary and relevant visualizations.

First the basic analysis of flight delay statistics:

In [13]: 
from IPython.display import Image

A histogram of average delay times in the top 20 airports:

In [13]: 
Image("../visualizations/histogram-avg-delay-times.png")
Out[13]:

The next chart represents average delay times (airports on x-axis in alphabetical order), with non-delayed flights (0 delay) factored in. We see a clustering of average delays around 9-11 minutes, with a few unusually high airports, and unusually low airport. Note that the dotted line is the mean of the 20 airports.

In [3]: 
Image("../visualizations/index.png")
Out[3]:

And ordered by delay time:

In [5]: 
Image("../visualizations/avg-delay-ordered.png")
Out[5]:

This next chart is the same, but with non-delayed flights removed from the averages. Notice that there are some airports, like ATL, that change substantially relative to the other airports. Airports that have a high (relative) average time with non-delayed flights included, but a lower (relative) time with non-delayed flights removed likely have a high proportion of delayed flights but relatively small delays. An airport that has a low (relatively) average time with non-delayed flights inluded, but a lower (relative) time with non-delayed flights remove likely has a lower proportion of delayed flights, but relatively large delays.

In [4]: 
Image("../visualizations/plot-avg-delay-times.png")
Out[4]:

And ordered by delay time, with only non-delayed flights:

In [3]: 
Image("../visualizations/avg-delay-ordered-no-ontime.png")
Out[3]:

This next chart displays the proportion of flights delayed, by airport.

In [5]: 
Image("../visualizations/proportion-flights-delayed.png")
Out[5]:
These proportions ordered:
In [9]: 
Image("../visualizations/prop-delay-ordered.png")
Out[9]:

Let's next look at the correlation between average delay with on-time flights and average delay without. Are airports that are bad according to one metric also bad according to the other? The following graph plots the two metrics against each other, by airport. We see a reasonably strong positive correlation between average delays with and without on-time flights included. Thus it seems that while on an individual level, some airports may be misrepresented by one of the metrics, as a whole airports that are bad by one standard are similarly bad by the other.

In [6]: 
Image("../visualizations/all-vs-delayed.png")
Out[6]:

Let's also look at the relationship between the proportion of flights delayed at an airport and the average delay among flights delayed. We see a relatively weak, but still evident negative correlation. Thus it seems that airports with more flights delayed may have less severe delays. This is very interesting! We see the greater proportion of flights delayed actually suggests lower average delay time for flights delayed, in contrast with the positive correlation of average delay time for all flights vs. proportion of flights delayed. Don't put too much faith in this, however, this corerlation is pretty weak, and visual examination of the scatter barely shows a negative relationship.

In [7]: 
Image("../visualizations/prop-vs-delay.png")
Out[7]:

Next, we'll look at how the delays scale. In order to do so, we'll examine the proportion of delays of at least x minutes, as x grows from 1 to 60.

In [10]: 
Image("../visualizations/proportion-delayed-over-x.png")
Out[10]:

Pretty standard. Now, we'll look at it with individual airports separated out:

In [11]: 
Image("../visualizations/proportion-delayed-over-x-all.png")
Out[11]:

We can see that the airports largely follow the same curve, with different proportions. There are a few crossovers, but no large deviations. The major difference in the chart between lines is vertical: thus some have more delays and some have less, but no airports have a markedly different distribution of delays. Except, it seems, at the high end. Those differences, proportionally speaking, look like they could be rather large.

So we'll redo the scale and axes to look at that portion.

In [12]: 
Image("../visualizations/prop-delayed-tail.png")
Out[12]:

The difference that seemed potentially dramatic no longer looks as dramatic. All the same, the difference in proportion of delays over 1 hour long still looks to be about double between the highest and lowest, which could be quite significant. These airports are SLC (lowest), at about 3%, and ORD, followed closely by EWR (highest), each over 6%. It looks like there are many more extreme delays, in fact about twice as many, at some airports, compared to others.

And a time-series related graphs:

In [16]: 
Image("../visualizations/time-series-1-resized.png")
Out[16]:

From the graph, it appears that the length of average delay time has clearly increased over all observations (~ 6.5 million!) over time.

In [17]: 
Image("../visualizations/time-series-2-resized.png")
Out[17]:

Time is a significant factor on proportions of flights delayed. There is a significant decrease (since the slope from the coefficients, years, is negative and the p-value is significant (p=.00575<.01)) in proportion of flights delayed over time. Once again, this is very interesting because we previously saw from the graph above the average length of delays has increased over time. Overall, there appear to be fewer delays but the delays are getting longer over time. More detailed analysis of the time series can be seen in NB3.

Conclusions

In our data analysis, we first looked at the average delay times at each airport over the 20-year time span. When we looked at average delay times, including flights that were not delayed (set at 0), we found that the airports with the longest average delays were Chicago O'Hare, Newark Liberty, Philadelphia, and Atlanta, and that those with the shortest average delays were Salt Lake City, George Bush Intercontinental (in Houston), Minneapolis-Saint Paul, and Los Angeles.

When we removed the flights that were not delayed and recalculated the average delay times of only delayed flights, the airports with the longest average delays were Newark, Chicago, Boston Logan, and Detroit, and the airports with the shortest average delays were Pitrsburgh, Salt Lake City, Charlotte, and Los Angeles. Notice that there is some overlap, namely Newark and Chicago for the worst airports and Salt Lake City and Los Angeles for the best airports. This is an indication that the airports' quality based on each of these metrics is not independent: being bad at one is a somewhat good indicator of being bad at another. In fact, as noted above, there is a fairly strong correlation between the two.

Next, we looked at the proportion of flights delayed of all departing flights from each airport over the 20-year time span. We found that the airports with the highest proportion of delayed flights were Atlanta, Pittsburgh, Charlotte, and Chicago, and that airports with the lowest proportion of delayed flights were Minneapolis-Saint Paul, Lambert-St. Louis, La Guardia (New York), and George Bush (Houston).

It was interesting to note that some airports had high average delay times and low proportion of flight delays, and vice versa. For example, Pittsburgh International Airport has the lowest average delay time (with non-delayed times removed from the calculation), but it has the second-highest proportion of flights delayed at more than 50%. Other airports were consistent in both metrics though. Chicago O'Hare International Airport ranks higly in delay times and proportion of flights delayed, and Los Angeles International Airport has both low average delay times and proportion of flights delayed.

The time-series graphs reveal that, between 1987 and 2008, the proportion of flights delays have been generally increasing across the major U.S. airports, and that average flight delay times have been generally decreasing.

It's difficult for us to declare one singular airport as the "worst" among the busiest airports in America, becuase each metric reveals just one of the many facets that determine a timely and consistent airport. But our data anaylsis corroborates our conclusion that Chicago O'Hare and Newark airports perform the worst in terms of average delay times, and Alanta and Pittsburgh airports in terms of proportion of flights delayed. However, Chicago O'Hare (ORD) not only had high average delay times with and without on-time flights removed, it also had a fairly high proportion of flights delayed.

Depending on how much credence you give to each factor, however, your mileage may vary. For example, the goal of a traveler may be to get to a destination by a certain time. In this case, given that a savvy traveler will budget extra time for contingencies, a high likelihood of a small delay may be tolerable, but the possibility of a very long delay is inexcusable. As a result, this traveler may put the most emphasis on proportion of very long delays when naming the worst airport. Or, an efficiency expert may care only about the overall average delay. Perhaps his or her interests lie in minimizing delay across the board, and thus the raw average statistic is the most important in determining the worst airport.

Simply put, there is no objective measure. But based on our investigation, we'll tentatively name ORD as the worst airport due to being bad by all metrics, with EWR as a very close second simply due to how much higher its delays were compared to all of the other airports.

Contact

If you would like more information about this project, or if you have any questions in general, send an email to any of us and we'll be sure to get back to you!

About Us

Connie Fee graduated UC Berkeley in 2014 with a degree in psychology. She hopes to go into education or teaching as a career. Contact: cfee92@berkeley.edu

Jonathan Chen is pursuing a double major in statistics and economics at UC Berkeley. He enjoys running, playing volleyball, and practicing guitar in his free time. Contact: jonathanchen@berkeley.edu

Bob Shao is a double major in statistics and economics at UC Berkeley. He is nationally ranked in chess and likes playing soccer and other sports. Contact: bobshao@berkeley.edu

Steven Hu is a statistics major at UC Berkeley. Contact: stevenhu03@berkeley.edu

entry.title: Data Analysis
entry.summary:
Team members responsible for this notebook:

  • Steven Hu: importing data, discussion of tests and conclusions that need to be done, the rainbow graphs (proportion delayed over x minutes)
  • Bob Shao: labeling/coloring for graphs for Airline Comparisons,Time Series Analysis, writeup of reasons and conclusions for tests
  • Connie Fee: reading of .csv files, generation of graphs, tables, and histograms for Airline Comparisons

Our primary goal was to investigate delays, both by airport and over time. The core question we try to address is:

  • Which of the major US airports is the worst, in terms of delayed flights?

Note that since our data encompasses an entire population (domestic commercial flights in the US from 1987-2008), many avenues of statistical inference become unnecessary. There's nothing probabalistic that comes into play when we have a comprehensive view of the population.

We will look at perhaps the simplest measure of "worst" first, the mean delay time at each airport.

In [2]: 
%load_ext rmagic

Import cleaned data:

In [3]: 
%%R
ATL=read.csv("../data/cleaned/ATL.csv",header=FALSE)
BOS=read.csv("../data/cleaned/BOS.csv",header=FALSE)
CLT=read.csv("../data/cleaned/CLT.csv",header=FALSE)
DEN=read.csv("../data/cleaned/DEN.csv",header=FALSE)
DFW=read.csv("../data/cleaned/DFW.csv",header=FALSE)
DTW=read.csv("../data/cleaned/DTW.csv",header=FALSE)
EWR=read.csv("../data/cleaned/EWR.csv",header=FALSE)
IAH=read.csv("../data/cleaned/IAH.csv",header=FALSE)
LAS=read.csv("../data/cleaned/LAS.csv",header=FALSE)
LAX=read.csv("../data/cleaned/LAX.csv",header=FALSE)
LGA=read.csv("../data/cleaned/LGA.csv",header=FALSE)
MSP=read.csv("../data/cleaned/MSP.csv",header=FALSE)
ORD=read.csv("../data/cleaned/ORD.csv",header=FALSE)
PHL=read.csv("../data/cleaned/PHL.csv",header=FALSE)
PHX=read.csv("../data/cleaned/PHX.csv",header=FALSE)
PIT=read.csv("../data/cleaned/PIT.csv",header=FALSE)
SEA=read.csv("../data/cleaned/SEA.csv",header=FALSE)
SFO=read.csv("../data/cleaned/SFO.csv",header=FALSE)
SLC=read.csv("../data/cleaned/SLC.csv",header=FALSE)
STL=read.csv("../data/cleaned/STL.csv",header=FALSE)
In [4]: 
%%R
airports=rbind(ATL,BOS,CLT,DEN,DFW,DTW,EWR,IAH,LAS,LAX,LGA,MSP,ORD,PHL,PHX,PIT,SEA,SFO,SLC,STL)
delay=c(airports$V4)
origin=c(as.character(airports$V1))
data=data.frame(delay=delay,origin=origin)

Airline Comparisons¶

First, we compared each airport's average delay time per flight:

In [4]: 
%%R
avgs=tapply(data$delay,data$origin,mean)
print(avgs)

      ATL       BOS       CLT       DEN       DFW       DTW       EWR       IAH 
11.270744 10.601876  9.752695 10.276824 10.202021 10.112165 12.504361  8.639502 
      LAS       LAX       LGA       MSP       ORD       PHL       PHX       PIT 
10.016496  9.064853  9.916390  8.880639 12.919656 11.849546  9.702281  9.381067 
      SEA       SFO       SLC       STL 
 9.485587 10.903367  7.865211  9.216288
In [38]: 
%%R
hist(avgs,xlab="Average Delay Time (min)",main="Histogram of Average Delay Times")
In [37]: 
%%R
plot(unique(data$origin),avgs,main="Average Delay Times by Airport",xlab="Airport",ylab="Average Delay Time (min)",xaxt='n')
text(unique(data$origin),avgs,unique(data$origin),cex=0.8, pos=4,col="blue")
abline(h=mean(avgs),lty=2)
text(18, 10.15, "Average delay time", col = "red")

It seems that there's a decent spread between the lowest and highest averages, from about 8 for SLC to about 13 for ORD. However, examining the means is quite simplistic by itself. The inclusion of 0 delay flights (undelayed) in the means lacks some resolution in evaluating the delays per airport. The raw means fail to distinguish between airports with a large proportion of slightly delayed flights and a small proportion of heavily delayed flights.

In order to look more closely at the data, we'll examine two additional factors:

  • Average delay, only including flights that have been delayed (at least 1 minute)
  • Proportion of flights delayed

Below, the proportion of flights delayed by airport is plotted.

In [6]: 
%%R
carriers=unique(data$origin)
prop={}
for(i in 1:20){
    airport=data$delay[data$origin == carriers[i]]
    total=length(airport)
    del=length(airport[airport != 0])
    prop=c(prop,del/total)
    }
table=data.frame(carriers=carriers, proportiondelayed=prop)
print(table)

   carriers proportiondelayed
1       ATL         0.5295946
2       BOS         0.4195840
3       CLT         0.5165910
4       DEN         0.4626000
5       DFW         0.4965155
6       DTW         0.4151824
7       EWR         0.4359185
8       IAH         0.4093387
9       LAS         0.4269760
10      LAX         0.4418887
11      LGA         0.4081828
12      MSP         0.3720727
13      ORD         0.5053018
14      PHL         0.4994521
15      PHX         0.4338250
16      PIT         0.5197303
17      SEA         0.4156508
18      SFO         0.4516042
19      SLC         0.4249509
20      STL         0.3957319
In [14]: 
%%R
plot(table$carriers,table$prop,main="Proportion of Flights Delayed by Airport",xlab="Airport",ylab="Proportion delayed",xaxt='n')
text(table$carriers,table$prop,unique(data$origin),cex=0.8, pos=4,col="blue")
abline(h=mean(table$prop),lty=2)
text(5, 0.449, "Average proportion delayed", col = "red")

Let's now plot Average Delay Times vs. Proportion of Flights Delayed:

In [36]: 
%%R
cat("Correlation:",cor(table$prop,avgs))
plot(table$prop,avgs,xlab="Proportion of Flights Delayed",ylab="Average Delay Time (min)",xlim=c(0.34,0.56),main="Average Delay Times vs. Proportion of Flights Delayed")
text(table$prop, avgs, carriers, cex=0.6, pos=4,col="blue")
res=lm(avgs~table$prop)
abline(res,lty=2)

Correlation: 0.4686857

We see a rough correlation: Higher Proportion of Flights Delayed generally suggests Higher Average Delay Time, although we see exceptions (e.g. SLC and ORD).

Next, we want to analyze the average delay time of each flight that was actually delayed:

In [28]: 
%%R
d=data
d[d==0]=NA
avgs2=tapply(d$delay,d$origin,mean,na.rm=TRUE)
print(avgs2)

     ATL      BOS      CLT      DEN      DFW      DTW      EWR      IAH 
21.28183 25.26759 18.87895 22.21536 20.54723 24.35596 28.68509 21.10600 
     LAS      LAX      LGA      MSP      ORD      PHL      PHX      PIT 
23.45915 20.51388 24.29399 23.86802 25.56819 23.72509 22.36450 18.04987 
     SEA      SFO      SLC      STL 
22.82105 24.14363 18.50852 23.28922
In [39]: 
%%R
plot(unique(data$origin),avgs2,main="Average Delay Times by Airport among Flights Delayed",xlab="Airport",ylab="Average Delay Time (min)",xaxt='n')
abline(h=mean(avgs2),lty=2)
text(unique(data$origin),avgs2,unique(data$origin),cex=0.8, pos=4,col="blue")
text(5, 22.65, "Average delay time", col = "red")

Let's now compare with this the Average Delay Time among all flights for an airport:

In [46]: 
%%R
cat("correlation:",cor(avgs,avgs2))
plot(avgs,avgs2,xlab="Average Delay Time of All Flights (min)",ylab="Average Delay Time (delay > 0 min)",main="Average Delay Time",xlim=c(7.5,13.5))
text(avgs, avgs2, carriers, cex=0.6, pos=4,col="blue")
res=lm(avgs2~avgs)
abline(res,lty=2)

correlation: 0.6527781

We see a rough correlation: Higher Average Delay Time of All Flights generally suggests Higher Average Delay Time for delayed flights, although we see exceptions (e.g. PIT and EWR).

Let's now compare Average Delay time for delayed flights with proportion of flights delayed:

In [49]: 
%%R
cat('correlation:',cor(table$prop,avgs2))
plot(table$prop,avgs2,xlab="Proportion of Flights Delayed",ylab="Average Delay Time (delay > 0 min)",main="Average Delay Time of Delayed Flights vs Proportion Delayed",xlim=c(0.35,0.55))
text(table$prop, avgs2, carriers, cex=0.6, pos=4,col='blue')
res=lm(avgs2~table$prop)
abline(res,lty=2)

correlation: -0.3590124

Very interesting! We see the greater proportion of flights delayed actually suggests lower average delay time for flights delayed! This is in contrast with the positive correlation we saw earlier of average delay time for all flights vs. proportion of flights delayed.

Finally, let's plot everything side by side for comparsion:

In [56]: 
%%R
par(mfrow=c(1,3))
plot(unique(data$origin),avgs,main="Delay Time: All Flights",xlab="Airport",ylab="Average Delay Time (min)",xaxt='n')
text(unique(data$origin),avgs,unique(data$origin),cex=0.8, pos=3,col="blue")
plot(unique(data$origin),avgs2,main="Delay Time: Flights Delayed",xlab="Airport",ylab="Average Delay Time (min)",xaxt='n')
text(unique(data$origin),avgs2,unique(data$origin),cex=0.8, pos=3,col="blue")
plot(table$carriers,table$prop,main="Proportion Delayed",xlab="Airport",ylab="Proportion delayed",xaxt='n')
text(table$carriers,table$prop,unique(data$origin),cex=0.8, pos=3,col="blue")

Next, let's examine the spread of delays at each airport. What we're interested in is how often delays of various severities occur. So, find proportions for each airport of flights delayed at least x minutes, as x goes from 1 to 60.

Note that for the following section the code wasn't originally run in this notebook, so to avoid the long runtime we've included the code but imported the output.

In []: 
%%R
airport = unique(data$origin)
In []: 
%%R
# NOTE: THIS CODE TAKES A LONGGGG TIME TO RUN. TRY TO AVOID USING IT AGAIN. THE LIST IT PULLS, a, IS IN data/cleaned as "output"
a = replicate(20, c())
names(a) = airport
for (n in 1:60) {
    for (i in airport) {  
        a[[i]] = c(a[[i]], sum(data$delay[data$origin == i] >= n)/length(data$delay[data$origin == i]))
    }
}

props = c()
for (n in 1:60) {
    props = c(props, sum(airports$V4 >= n)/length(airports$V4))
}

The code above pulls a list of vectors, each vector representing an airport and consisting of the proportion of flights from that airport delayed more than x minutes, x ranging from 1 to 60. It also pulls overall proportions of flights delayed over x minutes, x ranging from 1 to 60.

First, let's plot the overall proportions.

In []: 
%%R
plot(props, type="l", main="Proportion of Delayed Flights",xlab="Minimum Delay Time (minutes)",ylab="Proportion")
In [2]: 
from IPython.display import Image
Image("../visualizations/proportion-delayed-over-x.png")
Out[2]:

Next is a plot with proportions for each of the 20 airports separated.

In []: 
%%R -h 700 -w 700
color = rainbow(20)
plot(a[[1]], type="l", main="Proportion of Delayed Flights",xlab="Minimum Delay Time (minutes)",ylab="Proportion",col=color[1])
for (i in 2:20) {
    points(1:60, a[[i]], type="l", col=color[i-1])
}
In [3]: 
Image("../visualizations/proportion-delayed-over-x-all.png")
Out[3]:

We can see that the airports largely follow the same curve, with different proportions. There are a few crossovers, but no large deviations. The major difference in the chart between lines is vertical: thus some have more delays and some have less, but no airports have a markedly different distribution of delays. Except, it seems, at the high end. Those differences, proportionally speaking, look like they could be rather large.

So we'll redo the scale and axes to look at that portion.

In []: 
%%R -h 700 -w 700
color = rainbow(20)
plot(30:60,a[[1]][30:60], type="l", main="Proportion of Delayed Flights",xlab="Minimum Delay Time (minutes)",ylab="Proportion",ylim=c(0,.15),col=color[1])
for (i in 2:20) {
    points(30:60, a[[i]][30:60], type="l", col=color[i-1])
}
In [4]: 
Image("../visualizations/prop-delayed-tail.png")
Out[4]:

The difference that seemed potentially dramatic no longer looks as dramatic. All the same, the difference in proportion of delays over 1 hour long still looks to be about double between the highest and lowest, which could be quite significant. These airports are SLC (lowest), at about 3%, and ORD, followed closely by EWR (highest), each over 6%. It looks like there are many more extreme delays, in fact about twice as many, at some airports, compared to others. This could potentially be an important factor in deciding the worst airport.

Time Series Analysis¶

We want to analyze the trend of average delay time among flights over the time period (1987-2008). We used the SMA() function in the "TTR" R package to fit a smooth series data using a simple moving average. We are trying to find the trend component of this time series accounting for random fluctations.

In [5]: 
%%R
t1987=airports$V4[airports$V2 == 1987]
t1988=airports$V4[airports$V2 == 1988]
t1989=airports$V4[airports$V2 == 1989]
t1990=airports$V4[airports$V2 == 1990]
t1991=airports$V4[airports$V2 == 1991]
t1992=airports$V4[airports$V2 == 1992]
t1993=airports$V4[airports$V2 == 1993]
t1994=airports$V4[airports$V2 == 1994]
t1995=airports$V4[airports$V2 == 1995]
t1996=airports$V4[airports$V2 == 1996]

From the graph, it appears that the length of average delay time has clearly increased over all observations (~ 6.5 million!) over time

Next, we used the HoltWinters() function in R to find a simple exponential smoothing predicitive model:

The key value we are interested in is alpha. It's value of ~.0329 tells that slightly more weight is based on recent observations then less recent observations (This makes sense from the above graph, since there appears to be a clearly increasing trend)

Let's finally look at the SSE (Sum of Squared Errors) of the time series:

In []:

[1] 40928517890

** Logistic regression using log-odds success **¶

We are using a generalized linear model with log-odds success of proportions flights delayed as function over time. The linear probability model is not a good fit becuase probabilities are bound between 0 and 1. We used the simplest logit function: log(p/(1-p)), where p is defined as the proportion of flights delayed.

See: http://pages.uoregon.edu/aarong/teaching/G4075_Outline/node16.html

entry.title: Data Cleaning
entry.summary:
Team members responsible for this notebook:

  • Steven Hu: Writeup, code for cleaning
  • Bob Shao: Deciding what/how to clean
  • Connie Fee: Deciding what/how to clean

We've already done a lot of the organizing of the data we want when we pulled the csv files from the database in the previous notebook. But we still need to do a little more cleaning/filtering of the data.

First, let's just get an idea of what our data really looks like, in terms of flight departure delays. For now, we'll just look at the flights originating from ATL

In [2]: 
%load_ext rmagic
In [27]: 
%%R
data = read.csv('../data/raw/ATL.csv', header=F)
plot(data$V4)

We'll assume ATL is somewhat representative of other airports. The graph shows that there are clear outliers, particularly on the low end. Graphically, we can see that almost all of the data (there are over 6 million points here) are between -60 and 500. So we will set those arbitrary cutoffs for deleting outliers. The following plot for another airport shows something similar.

In [28]: 
%%R
data = read.csv('../data/raw/SLC.csv', header=F)
plot(data$V4)
In [7]: 
import sqlite3
database = sqlite3.connect('../data/raw/ontime.sqlite3')
cur = database.cursor()
cur.execute('SELECT Count(*) FROM ontime WHERE (DepDelay < -60) AND (Cancelled = 0)')
print cur.fetchone()

(889,)
In [6]: 
cur.execute('SELECT Count(*) FROM ontime WHERE (DepDelay > 500) AND (Cancelled = 0)')
print cur.fetchone()

(17099,)

As you can see, in the entire database there are 889 non-cancelled flights with departure delays of less than -60 minutes, and 17099 flights with non-cancelled departure delays of over 500 minutes. Therefore, based on the graphical representation and these figures, it seems reasonable to use these cutoffs to remove extreme outliers.

The traditional outlier cutoffs, \(Q3 + 1.5IQR\) on the high end or \(Q1 - 1.5IQR\) on the low end, don't really work here. This is because of the high quantity of numbers close to 0 in our data. The vast majority of flights are on-time or close to on-time, so the high-end outlier cutoffs, by this standard, end up somewhere between 17 and 30 minutes, depending on the individual airports.

This is an unreasonably low cutoff for removal from our data. 30 minute, or even longer delays, are perfectly believable, and removing them from the data essentially removes a good portion of the data we're most concerned about: delayed flights. So we use our somewhat arbitrary cutoffs. Note that the main reason we're even removing outliers is not to remove their disproportionate effect on the data, but rather their high possibility of being errors, or reflecting a unique circumstance (e.g. cancelled/rescheduled flight being classified as delayed, and subsequently receiving a very high delay time in the data, or even a very large negative delay), rather than an actual delay in operations.

In [25]: 
import csv

airports = [u'ORD', u'ATL', u'DFW', u'LAX', u'PHX', u'DEN', u'DTW', u'IAH', u'MSP', u'SFO', u'STL', u'EWR', u'LAS', u'CLT', u'LGA', u'BOS', u'PHL', u'PIT', u'SLC', u'SEA']
for i in airports:
    read = open('../data/raw/%s.csv' % i,'r')
    write = open('../data/cleaned/%s.csv' % i, 'w')
    reader = csv.reader(read)
    writer = csv.writer(write)
    for j in reader:
        if j[3] == 'NA':
            continue
        elif int(j[3]) < 0:
            if int(j[3]) < -60:
                continue
            else:
                j[3] = 0
                writer.writerow(j[:4])
        elif int(j[3]) > 500:
            continue
        else:
            writer.writerow(j[:4])
    read.close()
    write.close()

This writes new, cleaned csv files. Cancelled flights are removed, flights outside (-60, 500) for delay are removed, and all negative delays (early flights) are set to 0. This is because in evaluating delayed flights, an early flight is essentially the same as an on-time flight. It doesn't make sense to say that an airport that has 3 flights, with delays -5, 0, and 5, has an average delay of 0 minutes. So all flights that are not delayed, even those that were early, will be treated as flights with 0 delay.

Other than this stuff, the data we need is all in good shape. No issues like missing fields.

In [10]:

ATL = read.csv('../data/cleaned/ATL.csv', header=F)
print(head(ATL))

entry.summary:
Team members responsible for this notebook:

  • Steven Hu: Writing up, creating database, bash script, code to interface with database
  • Bob Shao: Assisting with creating database

Description of the Data¶

We pulled flight data from 1987 to 2008 from http://stat-computing.org/dataexpo/2009/the-data.html, downloading all 20 years. The data came in archived/compressed .csv files (comma-separated variables).

The files contain data on domestic US flights from 1987 to 2008. The data from all years combined consist of over 100 million rows and 29 columns. Each row represents a flight. The columns include (but are not limited to) the following information:

  • Year
  • Month
  • Day of Month
  • Day of Week
  • Scheduled Departure Time
  • Actual Departure Time
  • Scheduled Arrival Time
  • Actual Arrival Time
  • Scheduled Flight Time
  • Actual Flight Time
  • Departure Delay
  • Arrival Delay
  • Airport of Origin
  • Destination Airport
  • Flight Distance
  • Flight Number

Creating the Database¶

Due to the large size of the raw data, we could not work with it directly in iPython Notebook. Instead, we turned to SQLite to construct an SQL database.

There's a bash script above that should do it if you run from iPython Notebook, but be warned that it will take a very long time. Below is an explanation.

Start sqlite3, create database
$ sqlite3 ontime.sqlite3

sqlite> create table ontime (

...> DayofMonth int,
...> DayOfWeek int,

...> CRSDepTime int,

sqlite> .import 2005.csv ontime

sqlite> create index year on ontime(year);
sqlite> create index origin on ontime(origin);
sqlite> create index uniquecarrier on ontime(uniquecarrier);
sqlite> create index month on ontime(month);

Now we have a database with the relevant raw flight data we downloaded. We can now access the data in iPython Notebook via Python commands, using the sqlite3 package.

Narrowing it Down¶

We don't want to look at all of the data, with its myriad columns, since it's not all relevant to our interests. We will narrow it down to fit the scope of our investigation. First of all, we are interested in classifying flights by their airport of origin. And we will look at the 20 airports with the most originating flights. So we produce a list of those airports as follows:
